04737nam a22005535i 9780822380559DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223805597 a10.1515/97808223805592doi  a(DE-B1597)554628  a(OCoLC)1158006163  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBL2480.M32bM37 2001 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a299/.371 aMasquelier, Adeline, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrayer Has Spoiled Everything :bPossession, Power, and Identity in an Islamic Town of Niger /cAdeline Masquelier. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b25 b&w photographs, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBody, Commodity, Text00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Terms -- tIntroduction -- t1 Bori, Power, and Identity in Dogondoutchi -- t2 Lost Rituals: Changing Topographies of Spirit/Human Interactions -- t3 Socializing the Spirits -- t4 The Everyday Life of Bori: Knowledge, Embodiment, and Quotidian Practice -- t5 Kinesthetic Appropriation and Embodied Knowledge: Baboule Spirits and the Making of Value -- t6 Taking Hold of the Kasuwa: The Ritual Economy of Bori in the Market -- t7 The Mirrors of Maria: Sweetness, Sexuality, and Dangerous Consumption -- t8 Lightning, Death, and the Politics of Truth: The Spirits of Rain -- tConclusion: Continuities and Discontinuities in Bori -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBori, in the Mawri society of Niger, are mischievous and invisible beings that populate the bush. Bori is also the practice of taming these wild forces in the context of possession ceremonies. In Prayer Has Spoiled Everything Adeline Masquelier offers an account of how this phenomenon intervenes-sometimes subtly, sometimes dramatically-in human lives, providing a constantly renewed source of meaning for Mawri peasants confronted with cultural contradictions and socio-economic marginalization.To explore the role of bori possession in local definitions of history, power, and identity, Masquelier spent a total of two years in Niger, focusing on the diverse ways in which spirit mediums share, transform, and contest a rapidly changing reality, threatened by Muslim hegemony and financial hardship. She explains how the spread of Islam has provoked irreversible change in the area and how prayer-a conspicuous element of daily life that has become virtually synonymous with Islamic practice in this region of west Africa-has thus become equated with the loss of tradition. By focusing on some of the creative and complex ways that bori at once competes with and borrows from Islam, Masquelier reveals how possession nonetheless remains deeply embedded in Mawri culture, representing more than simple resistance to Islam, patriarchy, or the state. Despite a widening gap between former ways of life and the contradictions of the present, it maintains its place as a feature of daily life in which villagers participate with varying degrees of enthusiasm and approval.Specialists in African studies, in the anthropology of religion, and in the historical transformations of colonial and postcolonial societies will welcome this study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aBori (Cult)zNigerzDogondoutchi. 0aMawri (African people)zNigerzDogondoutchixReligion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822380559zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822380559423Coveruhtt